sibility of conversion. Race became a matter of salvation and damnation.Britton intervenes in critical debates about the intersections of race and religion, as well as in discussions of the social implications of romance. Examining English translations of Calvin, treatises on the sacraments, catechisms, and sermons alongside works by Edmund Spenser, John Harrington, William Shakespeare, John Fletcher, and Phillip Massinger, Becoming Christian demonstrates how a theology of race altered a nation's imagination and literary landscape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aChristians in literature. 0aConversion in literature. 0aConversionxChristianityxHistory. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aJews in literature. 0aMuslims in literature. 0aRace in literature. 0aReligion and literaturezEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aReligion and literaturezEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 4aBaptism. 4aChurch of England. 4aEdmund Spenser. 4aEnglish literature. 4aJews. 4aMuslims. 4aRace. 4aRomance. 4aWilliam Shakespeare. 4aconversion. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071187540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823257171zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823257171423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823257171.jpg  a978-3-11-071187-5  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK